Git Commands with Purpose (Basic ‚Üí Pro Level)
‚úÖ 1Ô∏è‚É£ Basic Git Setup
Command	Purpose
git --version	Check installed Git version
git config --global user.name "Name"	Set username
git config --global user.email "email"	Set email
git config --list	Show Git configuration
git help <command>	Get help for any command
‚úÖ 2Ô∏è‚É£ Repository Creation
Command	Purpose
git init	Initialize new Git repository
git clone <repo-url>	Copy remote repo to local
git clone -b branch <url>	Clone specific branch

Used heavily with GitHub.

‚úÖ 3Ô∏è‚É£ File Tracking & Staging
Command	Purpose
git status	Check current changes
git add <file>	Add single file
git add .	Add all files
git add -A	Add all including deleted
git reset <file>	Unstage file
‚úÖ 4Ô∏è‚É£ Commit Operations
Command	Purpose
git commit -m "message"	Commit staged changes
git commit -am "msg"	Add + commit tracked files
git commit --amend	Modify last commit
‚úÖ 5Ô∏è‚É£ Branching (Very Important in DevOps)
Command	Purpose
git branch	List branches
git branch <name>	Create branch
git checkout <branch>	Switch branch
git checkout -b <name>	Create + switch
git switch <branch>	Modern branch switch
git switch -c <name>	Create + switch
git branch -d <branch>	Delete branch
‚úÖ 6Ô∏è‚É£ Merging & Rebase
Command	Purpose
git merge <branch>	Merge branch
git rebase <branch>	Reapply commits
git rebase -i	Interactive rebase
git merge --abort	Cancel merge
‚úÖ 7Ô∏è‚É£ Remote Repository
Command	Purpose
git remote -v	Show remote
git remote add origin <url>	Add remote
git remote remove origin	Remove remote
git fetch	Download changes
git pull	Fetch + merge
git push	Push changes
git push -u origin main	First push
git push origin branch	Push branch
‚úÖ 8Ô∏è‚É£ Undo Changes (Interview Favorite)
Command	Purpose
git restore <file>	Restore file
git checkout -- <file>	Old restore method
git reset --soft HEAD~1	Undo commit, keep changes
git reset --hard HEAD~1	Remove commit
git revert <commit>	Reverse commit safely
‚úÖ 9Ô∏è‚É£ Logs & History
Command	Purpose
git log	View commit history
git log --oneline	Short logs
git log --graph	Visual log
git show <commit>	Show commit
git blame <file>	Who changed file
‚úÖ üîü Stashing (Real-time production work)
Command	Purpose
git stash	Save temporary changes
git stash list	View stash
git stash pop	Restore stash
git stash apply	Apply stash
‚úÖ 1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ Tags (Release management)
Command	Purpose
git tag	List tags
git tag v1.0	Create tag
git push origin v1.0	Push tag

Used in CI/CD pipelines.

‚úÖ 1Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ Advanced (Pro Level DevOps)
Command	Purpose
git cherry-pick <commit>	Copy commit
git reflog	Recover lost commits
git diff	Show changes
git diff --staged	Staged changes
git clean -fd	Remove untracked
git bisect	Find bug commit
git worktree	Multiple working dirs


Upload a Folder to GitHub (CLI)
‚úÖ Case 1: Folder already inside your Git project

üëâ Copy and paste these:

cd path/to/your/repo

git add folder-name/

git commit -m "Added folder-name"

git push

If this is your first push:

git push -u origin main
‚úÖ Case 2: Folder is NOT a Git repo yet (most common)

üëâ Go inside your folder and push:

cd folder-name

git init

git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/repo-name.git

git add .

git commit -m "Initial commit"

git branch -M main

git push -u origin main
‚úÖ Quick check before pushing (recommended)
git status

git remote -v
‚ö†Ô∏è If folder is empty (Git will ignore it)

Create a dummy file:

touch .gitkeep

Then push again.

